<h2>Quickstart Guide</h2>

<p>Installing the vicancy widget is quick and commitment-free. Installation shouldn’t take longer then 3 minutes
  if you follow the steps below.</p>

<h3>Step 1 &mdash; Include the Library</h3>

<p>In order to integrate vicancy in your page, the first thing to do is to include the library. Copy and paste the
  script provided by us in our email into your page just before the closing <code>&lt;/body&gt;</code> tag.</p>

<p>It should look something like this:</p>
<pre>&lt;script async src=&quot;http://www.vicancy.com/assets/widget-api.js&quot; type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>

<h3>Step 2 &mdash; Setup the Trigger</h3>

<p>Next we need to set up a ‘trigger’ to know when to open the widget. Any html element can do this on click — a
  button, a text link, or even an image.</p>

<p>See how the trigger is put into the element in the example below:</p>

<p><strong>Before:</strong></p>
<pre>&lt;a href=&#39;#&#39;&gt;Open Widget&lt;a&gt;</pre>
<p><strong>After:</strong></p>
<pre>&lt;a href=&#39;#&#39; onclick=&#39;vicancy.open({});return false;&#39;&gt;Open Widget&lt;/a&gt;</pre>

<h3>Step 3 &mdash; Set User Params</h3>

<p>Finally we need to be able to tell each of your clients apart, so we can show the right widget to the right
  client. This involves some basic server-side code to swap in some variables in the 'trigger code' from step
  2.</p>

<p>All variables need to be in order, be comma-seperated, and be in parenthesis. Below is a list of all variables,
  as well as an example:</p>
